%%TITLE
Human papillomavirus prevalence and prognostic implication in oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinomas.
%%ABSTRACT
Human papillomavirus (HPV)-related oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) is associated with favorable survival. The purpose of this study was to evaluate the prevalence and prognostic significance of the HPV infection through both the p16 expression status and the oncogenic HPV DNA viral load.A retrospective chart review was conducted on all patients treated for oropharyngeal SCC between January 2007 and June 2009. P16 expression status by immunohistochemistry and HPV DNA viral load by quantitative polymerase chain reaction (qPCR) were evaluated on routine pretreatment tumor samples.One hundred thirty-three patients (94 men and 39 women) were included in the study. Mean age was 59 years. One hundred twenty-two lesions (92%) were localized to lymphoid areas. Sixty-seven patients (50%) were p16+, and 87 patients (65%) harbored HPV DNA. The p16+/HPV DNA+ profile (48%) was associated with the most favorable prognosis. HPV16 was responsible for the majority of the infections (89%).HPV is common among oropharyngeal SCC in France, and acts as an independent prognostic factor.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Patient selection
A retrospective chart review followed by a prospective survival data collection was conducted on all patients diagnosed or treated for an oropharyngeal SCC between January 2007 and June 2009 at the Gustave Roussy Insti- tute. Only patients presenting with single untreated pri- mary lesions of the oropharynx were considered eligible for the study. Routine pretreatment FFPE tumor samples were collected from the pathology archives and available amounts of tissue were assessed.
Formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded tissue sample preparation
A first 3-lm section stained with hematoxylin-eosin was obtained from each patient’s tissue sample and reviewed by the pathologist to ensure that the tumor core was reached. Tumor differentiation was scored on an ordinal scale as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated. The presence and degree of basaloid features were also noted as partially or fully developed, with the term basa- loid denoting SCC that exhibit lobular to solid growth with peripheral cellular palisading and tumor cells dem- onstrating prominent basophilia because of high nuclear
to cytoplasmic ratio. Areas of high tumor cell density (>50% of cells on high power field) were encircled and served as landmarks for sample macrodissection. The fol- lowing 3-lm section was used for immunohistochemistry (IHC) preparation. The paraffin block was then meticu-
lously macrodissected and the excess wax trimmed. Twenty serial 20-lm sections were immediately collected into labeled DNA-free, DNase-free, and RNase-free Eppendorf Safe-Lock Tubes (Eppendorf AG, Hamburg, Germany) for DNA extractions. A final hematoxylin- eosin stained 3-lm section was done to confirm that the tumor core was not exceeded. In order to avoid contami- nation, sterile disposable microtome blades and scalpels were changed before every block. The p16 expression was evaluated by the same pathologist and the HPV DNA viral load data were analyzed by the same bioengineer.
Both procedures were conducted simultaneously in sepa- rate laboratories and in an absolute blind fashion.
Evaluation of p16INK4A expression
p16INK4A-IHC was performed on a Dako Autostainer (Universal staining system, Dako Denmark A/S, Glostrup, Denmark), using the CINtec p16INK4a Histology Kit (Ref. 9511, Roche mtm laboratories AG, Heidelberg, Germany), in accord with both manufacturers’ recommendations. The previously prepared 3-lm paraffin sections were consecu- tively incubated in the prediluted CINtec p16INK4A pri- mary antibody (clone E6H4) for 30 minutes, in the CINtec visualization reagent for another 30 minutes, then in dia- minobenzidine (a peroxidase chromogene substrate) for 10 minutes. Slides were finally counterstained with hematox- ylin and washed. A p16-positive well-differentiated kerati- nizing SCC of the oral tongue was used as a positive con- trol, and negative controls were obtained by skipping the primary antibody reaction. Tumors were classified dichot- omously as either p16INK4A-positive (strong, diffuse, nu-
clear and cytoplasmic staining in >10% of carcinoma cells) or p16INK4A-negative.22
DNA extraction and purification
The genomic DNA (gDNA) extraction and purification procedures were initiated on the previously prepared FFPE sections using the Qiagen QIAamp DNA FFPE Tis- sue Kit (Qiagen N.V., Hilden, Germany), in accord with the manufacturer’s recommendations. Sample gDNA con- centrations were then measured using both spectrophoto- metric (Nanodrop) and fluorometric (Qu-Bit) techniques, and adequate dilutions were made in order to obtain a uniform 2 ng/ll sample concentration, suitable for the real-time quantitative polymerase chain reaction (qPCR) assay.
Detection of human papillomavirus DNA viral load using quantitative polymerase chain reaction
The E6/E7 regions of the 3 oncogenic HPV strains (16, 18, and 33) were targeted using the TaqMan PCR Core Reagents Kit (Ref. N8080228; Applied Biosystems, Carls- bad, CA). The adopted qPCR protocol was previously reported by Flores–Munguia et al23 and Lindh et al.24 The assay was first validated for each HPV subtype on a full range of plasmid concentrations tested in duplicate in 4 independent plates, in order to document both its repro- ducibility and repeatability. Cycle threshold values were interpreted in amplification plots using a fluorescence- analyzing software (FaM Reporter; TEOCO, Fairfax, VA), allowing to confirm probe cleavage. Assays with 200 copies/PCR revealed cycle threshold values ranging between 38 and 40. The detection threshold approximated 40 copies/PCR and was not influenced by the presence of human gDNA at 20 ng/PCR (Roche; ref. 11691112001, human gDNA). We subsequently decided to routinely perform 45 cycles to be more confident in our negative results. Crossed tests between different HPV subtypes at 105 copies/PCR were negative, thus demonstrating a high specificity of the assay. We used the gACTB (b-actin) as a housekeeping gene and obtained a range of standard curves (20 ng, 5 ng, 1.25 ng, 0.31 ng, and 0.078 ng/PCR),

We also obtained standard curves for a range of plasmid concentrations (105, 104, 2000, 400, and 80 copies/PCR), and verified that the 80 copies/PCR checkpoint was always positive. Primers and probes were synthesized by Sigma Aldrich Co., and all the nucleotide sequences are shown in Table 1. All samples were tested in duplicate, and the analysis was performed in an ABI PRISM 7700 Sequence Detector (Applied Biosystems). Quantitative HPV DNA viral load measures were obtained, and a semiquantitative categorization was adopted according to predefined cycle threshold values;
cycle threshold 45: , 38 cycle threshold <45: , 34 cycle threshold <38: , cycle threshold <34: . When contamination from plate loading was suspected,
the procedure was repeated on newly harvested FFPE samples. In addition, all the weakly HPV-positive samples ( ) were submitted to an independent confirmatory PCR in order to exclude all potential false positives.
Statistical analysis
Associations between the clinicopathological features and both the p16 expression and HPV DNA viral load statuses (positive or negative) were evaluated using the chi-square, Fisher, and t tests. The follow-up periods were estimated using the reverse Kaplan–Meier method. The endpoints of the prognostic analyses were the overall survival (OS) and progression-free survival (PFS). OS was defined as the time elapsed between the initial diag- nosis and the occurrence of death from any cause. Patients who were alive at the time of the last follow-up visit were censored at this date. PFS was defined as the time elapsed between the initial diagnosis and the first occurrence of an event such as tumor progression, recur- rence, death from any cause, or until the last follow-up visit for event-free patients. OS and PFS were estimated using the Kaplan–Meier method. The prognostic impact of the clinicopathological parameters, the p16 expression status, and the HPV DNA viral load status was tested in
univariate analysis using the Cox model. All parameters with a p value < .20 in univariate analysis were subse- quently tested in multivariate analysis in order to deter- mine their independent prognostic value. All the statistical tests were 2-sided, and hazard ratios (HRs) are presented
with 95% confidence intervals (CIs). Statistical analyses were performed with the SAS System, version 9.1.
Ethical considerations
According to the French legislation, the institutional review board gave its approval on the study protocol, and written informed consent was obtained from all the included patients as to the use of their tissue samples for research purposes. Patient confidentiality was protected.
